<font color="#FF0000">BLACK FLIGHT OFFICERS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Oct  7 23:03:35 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Angell,<br><br>
Vietnam was a place for survivors, soldiers, and buddies.  I guess the common need diminished all those perceived social biases.  Went through flight training with a black officer named Henry.  Super guy.  I could always depend on him.  Great sense of humor.  Henry was always proud that he had worked his way through college.  He always said the only one from his neighborhood.  Applied for pilot training through a billet in Officer Training School.<br><br>
Henry made a great pilot.  Went to Nam flying Caribous (twin engine transport.  Henry's only worries were he was going to have to carry bodies.  Unfortunately he did that a lot.  He never liked it. Other worry was getting shot down.  Not till the end of his tour did they hose him down.  He came through OK.<br><br>
Other Black Officers, all pilots from the Army, Air Force, and Navy super guys.  Took a lot of work to make the cut and anybody who did belonged.  Only one man that I knew, a young black officer, let the situation eat him alive until he separated from the service.  He had the talent, but he never accepted the white officers.<br><br>
I had the honor of being there when men like Chappy James was flying.  I am sure there were problems, but I never saw it in Nam or in any of the special units I was in.  We were hand selected so maybe I never got a look at the average guy.<br><br>
I never knew why, but there was very few black pilots in my units.<br><br>
After the war they were glad to home like the rest of us.  All were career officers.  They had worked so hard to get there they wanted to keep it.  Flight training and your wings treated everyone the same.  Talent, brains, capability, regardless of color to make the grade.  Anything less resulted in death.<br>

